00:36:50,405 --> 00:36:52,534
You said, "I don't follow baseball. "

496
00:36:52,685 --> 00:36:54,530
- How could you not?
- Why'd you kill Rufus?

497
00:36:54,686 --> 00:36:58,091
Over and over, it must have been
maybe a year, maybe more, I don't know.

498
00:36:58,247 --> 00:37:00,047
All I did was hear them in my head.

499
00:37:00,208 --> 00:37:03,296
What? What are you talking about?
Are you talking about McCain?

500
00:37:03,448 --> 00:37:04,812
I'm talking about baseball.

501
00:37:04,968 --> 00:37:07,217
I'm talking about
the great American pastime.

502
00:37:07,368 --> 00:37:10,217
I went over every game
I ever heard on the radio.

503
00:37:10,369 --> 00:37:12,334
I mean, I went over every game
I ever heard.

504
00:37:12,489 --> 00:37:14,858
Just playing them over and over
in my head.

505
00:37:16,450 --> 00:37:20,412
You had all those games to go to
and you didn't even care.

506
00:37:20,571 --> 00:37:22,459
Henri, I'm talking about Rufus McCain.

507
00:37:22,611 --> 00:37:26,136
And I'm talking about three fucking years
they had me in that bucket!

508
00:37:26,412 --> 00:37:29,774
Three fucking years!
Without any fucking light even!

509
00:37:29,933 --> 00:37:32,782
You had all those games to listen to!

510
00:37:33,134 --> 00:37:36,058
You don't even know
what DiMaggio hit this year.

511
00:37:38,055 --> 00:37:39,583
What kind of asshole are you?

512
00:37:41,295 --> 00:37:43,259
Calm down, boy.

513
00:37:44,975 --> 00:37:48,217
Do you know the average length
of time an inmate would be in solitary?

514
00:37:48,376 --> 00:37:49,380
Nineteen days.

515
00:37:49,536 --> 00:37:52,942
- I understand, but he killed a man.
- Young did more than three years.

516
00:37:53,097 --> 00:37:56,458
- Three years in total darkness.
- That's tragic, but he took a life.

517
00:37:56,617 --> 00:37:59,379
Your brother's gonna tell you
you're not gonna get him off.

518
00:37:59,538 --> 00:38:02,387
My brother is the best lawyer
I know. Somebody to tell me...

519
00:38:02,539 --> 00:38:05,224
...we've got a chance
for some kind of insanity plea.

520
00:38:05,380 --> 00:38:07,060
Your brother's not gonna give a damn.

521
00:38:07,220 --> 00:38:09,184
Your client is a two-time loser.

522
00:38:09,340 --> 00:38:13,225
This case is much more
about you than him.

523
00:38:13,381 --> 00:38:15,389
He has no future.

524
00:38:15,541 --> 00:38:19,066
This is your first time in the spotlight.
It's what you worked for.

525
00:38:19,222 --> 00:38:25,148
This case is a lost cause,
so you must handle it like a lost cause.

526
00:38:30,984 --> 00:38:34,674
Maybe you're right, but the guy's
not exactly Al Capone, you know.

527
00:38:34,825 --> 00:38:36,866
No. No, he isn't.

528
00:38:37,026 --> 00:38:39,230
All they had him on
was income tax evasion.

529
00:38:39,386 --> 00:38:43,228
Your boy, they got on murder one.

530
00:38:44,066 --> 00:38:45,791
Hi. How are you?

531
00:38:45,947 --> 00:38:47,552
Hi, Henri.

532
00:38:47,707 --> 00:38:48,875
Hey, listen.

533
00:38:49,027 --> 00:38:51,396
You're not mad at me
for blowing up at you yesterday?

534
00:38:51,548 --> 00:38:53,557
Because, you know, nobody talks back.

535
00:38:53,708 --> 00:38:55,269
Mad at you? No, I'm not mad at you.

536
00:38:55,429 --> 00:38:58,070
And I'll get the hang of it.
I got a sense of humor.

537
00:38:58,229 --> 00:39:00,630
We gonna have some good times
before this is through.

538
00:39:00,790 --> 00:39:02,831
You know how to play cards?
Could you get some?

539
00:39:02,991 --> 00:39:05,479
Look, look, look, I set this up for you.
Here, sit down.

540
00:39:05,630 --> 00:39:08,195
How much light got into the cell
you spent three years in?

541
00:39:08,351 --> 00:39:10,435
Like when you offered me that cigarette.

542
00:39:10,592 --> 00:39:12,796
I said, no, that shit will kill you.
That was pretty good.

543
00:39:12,952 --> 00:39:16,041
Henri, you gotta help me
if I'm gonna defend you, okay?

544
00:39:16,192 --> 00:39:17,797
Yeah, sure, sure.
- All right.

545
00:39:19,233 --> 00:39:20,958
Look here.

546
00:39:22,274 --> 00:39:25,635
Did you kill this man here?
Rufus McCain?

547
00:39:26,435 --> 00:39:28,355
I must have. I'm here.

548
00:39:28,515 --> 00:39:31,080
I don't remember it,
but everybody saw me, so, yeah.

549
00:39:31,555 --> 00:39:33,564
- But you don't remember it?
- No. But so what?

550
00:39:33,716 --> 00:39:34,764
Did you want to?

551
00:39:34,916 --> 00:39:37,961
You know, once there was this spider
that crawled over me.

552
00:39:38,116 --> 00:39:39,557
It was like having company.

553
00:39:39,717 --> 00:39:42,479
I looked for him again. I couldn't find him.
He had a way out.

554
00:39:42,637 --> 00:39:44,841
McCain was the reason
you landed in the bucket.

555
00:39:44,998 --> 00:39:46,798
One hundred forty-two times 93. Ask me.

556
00:39:46,958 --> 00:39:50,560
- How long after you came out of the hole-?
-13,206.

557
00:39:51,120 --> 00:39:53,924
Thirteen thousand. You mean, days?
What are you talking about'?

558
00:39:54,080 --> 00:39:56,241
That's the answer, 142 times 93.

559
00:39:56,400 --> 00:39:59,445
- Henri, concentrate on what I'm saying.
- I know what you're saying.

560
00:39:59,601 --> 00:40:02,602
- How long was it?
- I don't know. Okay? I don't remember.

561
00:40:02,762 --> 00:40:06,451
Hey, what's this new girl
I've seen in the papers? This Ingrid Berger?

562
00:40:06,602 --> 00:40:08,763
She's some kind of looker.
You seen the movies?

563
00:40:08,923 --> 00:40:11,891
- Goddamn it. I want you to think.
- I don't wanna think!

564
00:40:12,043 --> 00:40:17,086
I spent three goddamn years in the dark,
smelling my own shit and piss...

565
00:40:17,244 --> 00:40:18,805
...doing nothing but thinking.

566
00:40:18,965 --> 00:40:20,689
I hate thinking.

567
00:40:27,006 --> 00:40:29,015
I'm sorry, Henri.

568
00:40:34,007 --> 00:40:35,491
I'm sorry.

569
00:40:36,488 --> 00:40:38,529
I'm just trying to help you.

570
00:40:38,688 --> 00:40:41,012
Hey, you got a girl, right?

571
00:40:42,168 --> 00:40:44,373
- Yeah.
- Take your jacket off.

572
00:40:44,529 --> 00:40:46,538
- What?
- Let me smell it.

573
00:40:46,690 --> 00:40:48,655
You were easier to understand catatonic.

574
00:40:48,810 --> 00:40:50,294
- What's she like?
- Who?

575
00:40:50,450 --> 00:40:53,855
Your girl. That's perfume on your jacket
Let me smell your jacket.

576
00:40:55,811 --> 00:40:57,055
Look, I'll make you a deal.

577
00:40:57,212 --> 00:41:00,453
I'll give my jacket, pants,
whatever you want. Sports, girls, whatever.

578
00:41:00,612 --> 00:41:03,253
But you gotta tell me just one memory
about something I ask.

579
00:41:03,813 --> 00:41:06,979
- Deal?
- Sure.

580
00:41:07,614 --> 00:41:09,338
Okay.

581
00:41:14,295 --> 00:41:15,855
I never been with a girl, you know.

582
00:41:23,096 --> 00:41:24,984
Let me try it on.

583
00:41:25,697 --> 00:41:28,021
How long was it
that you went without any daylight?

584
00:41:28,177 --> 00:41:30,065
Did they ever let you out
for any exercise?

585
00:41:30,898 --> 00:41:33,266
- Aah! Please, don't hit me.
- Merry Christmas.

586
00:41:33,419 --> 00:41:36,180
- Get the tear gas.
- How long I been in here?

587
00:41:36,339 --> 00:41:39,024
- You're out of the hole.
- I made it. I did it.

588
00:41:39,180 --> 00:41:43,229
It's Christmas, 1940.
You've been down there two years.

589
00:41:44,060 --> 00:41:45,828
Two years.

590
00:41:45,981 --> 00:41:47,868
I did it.

591
00:41:48,381 --> 00:41:50,543
Two fucking years.

592
00:41:50,781 --> 00:41:53,466
I made it. I made it.

593
00:41:53,623 --> 00:41:56,068
I'm not too crazy, am I?

594
00:41:56,223 --> 00:41:58,068
I did it. It's over.

595
00:41:58,223 --> 00:41:59,664
Nothing's over, Henri.

596
00:41:59,823 --> 00:42:03,064
Thirty minutes exercise,
that's all you get.

597
00:42:03,224 --> 00:42:08,190
No!

598
00:42:08,345 --> 00:42:10,386
You don't want it, we take you back.

599
00:42:10,545 --> 00:42:12,826
No, no. I want it.

600
00:42:12,985 --> 00:42:14,710
I want it.

601
00:42:15,666 --> 00:42:17,708
I'll be good. I'll-

602
00:42:26,068 --> 00:42:28,273
Ladies and gentlemen of the jury...

603
00:42:28,748 --> 00:42:33,791
...the defendant, Henri Young,
is accused of murder in the first degree.

604
00:42:33,950 --> 00:42:38,196
It is your responsibility as a juror
to deal with truth.

605
00:42:38,350 --> 00:42:42,596
Rufus McCain was murdered
by Henri Young.

606
00:42:42,751 --> 00:42:47,356
Mr. Stamphill, the public defender,
will play upon your sympathies.

607
00:42:47,513 --> 00:42:51,442
He will use every trick in the book. Why?

608
00:42:51,593 --> 00:42:53,797
To avoid the gas chamber.

609
00:42:53,954 --> 00:42:58,756
The United States of America will demand
that you return a verdict of guilty...

610
00:42:58,915 --> 00:43:02,243
...so that this... This animal...

611
00:43:02,395 --> 00:43:05,276
...will receive the punishment commanded
by the Bible.

612
00:43:05,876 --> 00:43:09,685
An eye for an eye. A life for a life.

613
00:43:09,837 --> 00:43:14,005
For if ever there was a man
guilty of murder...

614
00:43:14,157 --> 00:43:16,165
...it is Henri Young.

615
00:43:16,718 --> 00:43:20,887
And if ever a man deserved
to die for that crime...

616
00:43:21,038 --> 00:43:23,287
...it is the accused.

617
00:43:26,480 --> 00:43:30,005
Thank you very much, Mr. McNeil.

618
00:43:31,361 --> 00:43:35,529
Mr. Stamphill, are you prepared to make
your opening statement at this time?

619
00:43:35,682 --> 00:43:39,611
Your Honor, ladies and gentlemen
of the jury.

620
00:43:40,723 --> 00:43:45,011
When I was a kid, my heroes
weren't Babe Ruth or Lou Gehrig...

621
00:43:45,163 --> 00:43:47,050
...they were Clarence Darrow, Emile Zola.

622
00:43:47,204 --> 00:43:49,889
In other words, I have waited
for this moment all of my life.

623
00:43:50,044 --> 00:43:53,166
To stand like I am right now
in front of a jury of 12 good people...

624
00:43:53,325 --> 00:43:56,730
...to plead the case of an innocent man
who's been unjustly accused.

625
00:43:56,885 --> 00:43:59,286
The only problem is he did it.

626
00:43:59,446 --> 00:44:02,174
I know it, the prosecutor, Mr. McNeil,
knows it.

627
00:44:02,326 --> 00:44:06,332
Henri doesn't know it because he can't
remember it, but he won't deny he did it.

628
00:44:06,487 --> 00:44:09,696
All those witnesses the prosecutor's
going to bring forth will tell you.

629
00:44:09,847 --> 00:44:12,729
Henri Young killed Rufus McCain.

630
00:44:13,129 --> 00:44:16,414
So now that we all know that,
why don't we find the man guilty...

631
00:44:16,569 --> 00:44:19,570
...and gas him because that's
what we all know is going to happen?

632
00:44:19,729 --> 00:44:22,130
- Right, Henri?
- What?

633
00:44:23,131 --> 00:44:27,616
There's only one problem that's gonna keep
us from wrapping this up in record time.

634
00:44:27,771 --> 00:44:31,296
Henri Young did not act alone.
They haven't caught all the killers.

635
00:44:31,452 --> 00:44:32,773
There was a co-conspirator.

636
00:44:32,932 --> 00:44:36,380
It is because of this co-conspirator,
whom we shall name in this courtroom...

637
00:44:36,533 --> 00:44:38,978
...that Henri Young is innocent
of the crime of murder.

638
00:44:39,133 --> 00:44:40,093
What?

639
00:44:40,254 --> 00:44:42,535
Objection, Your Honor. I must protest.

640
00:44:42,694 --> 00:44:44,058
I kind of figured you would.

641
00:44:44,214 --> 00:44:46,015
Your Honor, this is absurd.

642
00:44:46,175 --> 00:44:49,897
Before the counselor is allowed to waste
this court's time and this jury's time...

643
00:44:50,055 --> 00:44:54,540
...I would request that he supply some proof
or evidence of this co-conspirator.

644
00:44:54,696 --> 00:44:56,944
Mr. Stamphill,
can you bring forward evidence...

645
00:44:57,097 --> 00:44:58,984
...of the existence of a co-conspirator?

646
00:44:59,137 --> 00:45:02,902
Not at this time, but it is my intention to
during the course of the trial.

647
00:45:03,058 --> 00:45:06,660
He's not going to provide such proof
because no proof exists.

648
00:45:06,818 --> 00:45:09,940
This man spent three years
in solitary confinement...

649
00:45:10,099 --> 00:45:12,904
...during which time
no one had any influence over him...

650
00:45:13,060 --> 00:45:16,105
...because no one had
any contact with him.

651
00:45:16,260 --> 00:45:18,945
He came out of solitary.
He went directly to a shower.

652
00:45:19,101 --> 00:45:23,183
Then he went directly to a haircut.
Then he went directly to the dining hall...

653
00:45:23,342 --> 00:45:26,191
...where one convict had said
one sentence to him.

654
00:45:26,342 --> 00:45:28,831
Your Honor, this does not
a co-conspirator make.

655
00:45:28,983 --> 00:45:32,104
I'm inclined to agree with the prosecution,
young man.

656
00:45:32,264 --> 00:45:34,425
Unless you can justify
that line of defense...

657
00:45:34,584 --> 00:45:37,225
...I will sustain
the prosecution's objection.

658
00:45:37,384 --> 00:45:41,269
The district attorney, with his own words,
has just made my case for me.

659
00:45:41,425 --> 00:45:43,466
That'll be the day.

660
00:45:43,626 --> 00:45:48,515
Your Honor, for three years,
three long, torturous years...

661
00:45:48,666 --> 00:45:52,388
...no one and nothing had any influence
whatsoever over Henri Young.

662
00:45:52,547 --> 00:45:53,988
No one and nothing.

663
00:45:54,147 --> 00:45:57,476
This was a man whose only crime
was to steal $5 from a local post office...

664
00:45:57,628 --> 00:45:59,669
...so he could feed his starving sister.

665
00:45:59,829 --> 00:46:02,469
He came to Alcatraz a petty criminal...

666
00:46:02,629 --> 00:46:06,154
...who had never harmed or attempted
to harm another human being in his life.

667
00:46:06,309 --> 00:46:09,878
And he came out of the dungeon
a vicious, barbaric, maniacal murderer.

668
00:46:10,030 --> 00:46:12,551
A man who had been put
into a kind of psychological coma.

669
00:46:12,711 --> 00:46:14,872
Within an hour of coming out
of that hellhole...

670
00:46:15,031 --> 00:46:18,153
...he did what would have been unthinkable
to him three years before.

671
00:46:18,312 --> 00:46:19,479
Unthinkable.

672
00:46:19,632 --> 00:46:22,840
His only thought was murder.
His only instinct was murder.

673
00:46:22,993 --> 00:46:24,641
His first act was murder.

674
00:46:24,793 --> 00:46:28,242
Now, he himself was a murder weapon,
but the hand that held that weapon...

675
00:46:28,393 --> 00:46:31,842
...and plunged it into the throat of
Rufus McCain belonged to someone else.

676
00:46:31,994 --> 00:46:35,519
I point to the associate warden, Mr. Glenn,
the warden, Mr. Humson...

677
00:46:35,675 --> 00:46:38,163
...and the institution Alcatraz,
and say, "I accuse. "

678
00:46:38,316 --> 00:46:41,120
Objection.
- I accuse them individually and collectively.

679
00:46:41,276 --> 00:46:43,841
I accuse Alcatraz of the torture
of Henri Young.

680
00:46:45,157 --> 00:46:47,318
I accuse Alcatraz of the murder
of Rufus McCain.

681
00:46:47,477 --> 00:46:50,959
Silence! This court will come to order.

682
00:46:51,118 --> 00:46:52,843
Clear the courtroom.

683
00:46:52,998 --> 00:46:55,443
Henri Young is not going to be
the only defendant here.

684
00:46:55,599 --> 00:46:57,847
No. Alcatraz is on trial.

685
00:46:58,079 --> 00:47:00,600
I will address your objection
tomorrow morning.

686
00:47:01,080 --> 00:47:02,880
Henri Young, on trial for his life...

687
00:47:03,040 --> 00:47:05,245
...is seen leaving
the San Francisco courthouse...

688
00:47:05,401 --> 00:47:09,363
...followed by his young and now very
popular public defender, James Stamphill.

689
00:47:09,522 --> 00:47:12,371
Stamphill has accused the infamous Rock
of torture...

690
00:47:12,522 --> 00:47:15,284
...using the tagline,
"crimes against humanity. "

691
00:47:15,442 --> 00:47:20,725
Stamphill has turned the once-quiet trial
of a convict killing into a media circus.

692
00:47:20,884 --> 00:47:23,045
In most cases, they do get better.

693
00:47:23,204 --> 00:47:27,330
And in the case of Henri Young, uh...

694
00:47:27,565 --> 00:47:29,649
...this happens not to be true.

695
00:47:29,806 --> 00:47:32,774
Young is a noisemaker.

696
00:47:32,926 --> 00:47:36,571
Some prisoners have a problem
when they're in, uh...

697
00:47:36,726 --> 00:47:38,134
...ahem, solitary.

698
00:47:38,287 --> 00:47:42,533
All we do
is try to discourage misconduct.

699
00:47:42,688 --> 00:47:44,336
This is the first verbal attack...

700
00:47:44,488 --> 00:47:46,333
...on the jewel of the prison system.

701
00:47:46,488 --> 00:47:50,690
This bastion that houses evil
opened in 1934.

702
00:47:50,849 --> 00:47:52,858
It brought gangsters like Capone...

703
00:47:53,010 --> 00:47:57,692
...Machine Gun Kelly and Henri Young
close to the magical city by the bay...

704
00:47:57,850 --> 00:48:01,256
...less than one half-mile
from world-famous Fisherman's Wharf.

705
00:48:01,411 --> 00:48:03,572
We went to the streets
to find out public opinion.

706
00:48:03,731 --> 00:48:07,256
That's ridiculous. You can't put a place
on trial. It's a prison for prisoners.

707
00:48:07,413 --> 00:48:10,382
Now the murderers are accusing
the wardens of this and that.

708
00:48:10,533 --> 00:48:12,334
That doesn't make a whole lot of sense.

709
00:48:12,493 --> 00:48:14,654
Warden Humson seems like a good guy.
I like him.

710
00:48:14,814 --> 00:48:16,779
If that place wasn't here,
I wouldn't live here.

711
00:48:16,934 --> 00:48:19,662
- You think it's too close?
- I think it's perfect.

712
00:48:19,815 --> 00:48:22,739
He's innocent until proven guilty
and he'll get a fair trial.

713
00:48:22,896 --> 00:48:24,904
But nonetheless, he's a murderer.

714
00:48:25,056 --> 00:48:27,304
This grizzly evidence bears mute witness...

715
00:48:27,456 --> 00:48:30,861
...to the brutal crime perpetrated
by Henri Young.

716
00:48:31,016 --> 00:48:32,937
Note the spoon.

717
00:48:33,097 --> 00:48:34,941
Can a prison be put on trial?

718
00:48:35,098 --> 00:48:37,499
Judge Clawson's ruling tomorrow
may clear the way...

719
00:48:37,658 --> 00:48:40,223
...to put Alcatraz on trial.

720
00:48:40,378 --> 00:48:45,267
"The warden can be relied upon
to carry out the instructions of the bureau...

721
00:48:45,419 --> 00:48:49,620
...that no brutality or inhumanity
shall be practiced.

722
00:48:49,781 --> 00:48:52,782
Sustained food and medical attention
shall be given. "

723
00:48:52,941 --> 00:48:56,390
And we have wholeheartedly
followed those instructions.

724
00:48:56,541 --> 00:48:57,742
Thank you.

725
00:48:57,901 --> 00:48:59,866
So many opinions being expressed.

726
00:49:00,022 --> 00:49:03,188
We attempted to get a statement
from the recent graduate of Harvard

727
00:49:03,343 --> 00:49:05,831
...assigned to defend Henri Young.

728
00:49:05,984 --> 00:49:08,953
Why don't we just keep the trial
in the courtroom? Thank you.

729
00:49:10,224 --> 00:49:11,905
I would like to address a few words...

730
00:49:12,064 --> 00:49:13,712
...to the counsel for the defense.

731
00:49:13,865 --> 00:49:16,146
Mr. Stamphill, you are hereby
put on notice...

732
00:49:16,305 --> 00:49:19,350
...that this court has no interest
in newspaper headlines...

733
00:49:19,506 --> 00:49:21,515
...and will not be swayed by them.

734
00:49:22,267 --> 00:49:26,916
And I further admonish that counsel's
attempts to try this case in the press...

735
00:49:27,067 --> 00:49:30,593
...and not before this court,
will put him in the utmost peril.

736
00:49:32,668 --> 00:49:34,393
Is that clear, Mr. Stamphill?

737
00:49:34,548 --> 00:49:35,628
Yes, Your Honor.

738
00:49:36,469 --> 00:49:37,833
Well, good.

739
00:49:38,109 --> 00:49:40,270
Bailiff, approach the bench.

740
00:49:40,429 --> 00:49:44,074
Before I hand down my ruling
on Mr. McNeil's objection...

741
00:49:44,231 --> 00:49:47,679
...I would like to address a few words
to the counsel for the defense.

742
00:49:47,831 --> 00:49:51,912
While I cannot give legal advice
and sit on the bench at the same time...

743
00:49:52,072 --> 00:49:56,482
...I will express grave concern
with the defense's strategy.

744
00:49:56,633 --> 00:49:59,361
Counselor, I strongly recommend
you walk a straight line...

745
00:49:59,513 --> 00:50:01,194
...in terms of your defense.

746
00:50:01,354 --> 00:50:05,916
Anything you state in this courtroom
will be evaluated not only by the jury...

747
00:50:06,074 --> 00:50:08,159
...but very closely scrutinized by myself.

748
00:50:08,315 --> 00:50:11,359
- Is that understood, Mr. Stamphill?
- Yes, Your Honor.

749
00:50:12,036 --> 00:50:13,640
Very well.

750
00:50:14,716 --> 00:50:17,444
Prosecution's objection is overruled.

751
00:50:17,596 --> 00:50:20,041
Mr. Stamphill, you may pursue
your line of defense...

752
00:50:20,197 --> 00:50:22,325
...concerning the penitentiary
at Alcatraz...

753
00:50:22,478 --> 00:50:26,003
...and I will rule on any objections
on a point-by-point basis.

754
00:50:26,158 --> 00:50:28,319
- Exception.
- Noted.

755
00:50:28,479 --> 00:50:30,967
Mr. McNeil, you may call
your first witness.

756
00:50:31,119 --> 00:50:34,088
Prosecution calls Terrence Swenson..

757
00:50:34,480 --> 00:50:36,761
Court calls Terrence Swenson..

758
00:50:44,802 --> 00:50:46,482
Witness shall remain standing...

759
00:50:46,642 --> 00:50:48,684
...until sworn in.

760
00:50:49,123 --> 00:50:50,728
Put your hand on the Bible.

761
00:50:50,883 --> 00:50:51,931
Cut it out.

762
00:50:52,083 --> 00:50:54,407
Swear to tell the truth
and nothing but the truth...

763
00:50:54,564 --> 00:50:56,888
...in the matter before this court,
so help you, God?

764
00:50:57,044 --> 00:51:00,210
So help me God.
- You may be seated.

765
00:51:00,725 --> 00:51:05,090
Mr. Swenson, as a guard at Alcatraz,
did you know Henri Young?

766
00:51:05,246 --> 00:51:08,815
- Yes, sir.
- Could you point him out for us?

767
00:51:09,446 --> 00:51:11,650
That's him right over there, sir.

768
00:51:11,807 --> 00:51:14,775
Thank you, Mr. Whitney. Thank you.

769
00:51:14,927 --> 00:51:18,212
Now, on the morning of June 11, 1941,
where were you?

770
00:51:18,648 --> 00:51:22,654
I was on duty in the dining hall.
And everything was normal.

771
00:51:23,049 --> 00:51:25,133
And I saw the defendant-

772
00:51:25,289 --> 00:51:27,374
- Henri Young.
- That's correct.

773
00:51:27,530 --> 00:51:30,095
I saw him standing over Rufus McCain.

774
00:51:30,251 --> 00:51:32,292
He lifted up his chin and...

775
00:51:32,451 --> 00:51:34,896
- Heh. Excuse me, I'm nervous.
- That's all right.

776
00:51:35,051 --> 00:51:38,096
And he plunged a metal object...

777
00:51:38,251 --> 00:51:41,896
...which I later learned was a spoon,
into McCain's throat.

778
00:51:42,733 --> 00:51:45,614
He then ripped it open.

779
00:51:45,774 --> 00:51:47,378
Did the defendant ever appear...

780
00:51:47,534 --> 00:51:49,139
...to be ranting or raving?

781
00:51:49,294 --> 00:51:50,418
No, sir.

782
00:51:50,575 --> 00:51:53,303
Mr. McKeon, was he frothing at the mouth?

783
00:51:53,455 --> 00:51:54,622
No, sir.

784
00:51:54,775 --> 00:51:58,103
Did he in any way give the impression
of one who was insane?

785
00:51:58,256 --> 00:52:01,421
Objection. This man is not
a qualified psychiatrist, as far as I know.

786
00:52:01,576 --> 00:52:02,580
Sustained.

787
00:52:02,737 --> 00:52:06,742
So it appeared to you that it was a cool,
calculated and deliberate act?

788
00:52:06,898 --> 00:52:08,982
- Objection.
- Overruled.

789
00:52:09,137 --> 00:52:10,905
The witness may answer the question.

790
00:52:11,058 --> 00:52:14,179
Yes, sir. Young did it,
just as cool as a cucumber.

791
00:52:14,338 --> 00:52:16,783
Thank you. No further questions.

792
00:52:17,299 --> 00:52:20,148
This court will reconvene after the holiday...

793
00:52:20,300 --> 00:52:22,144
...9 a. m., July 5th.

794
00:52:22,300 --> 00:52:25,389
All rise.
- You should have played cards with me.

795
00:52:25,941 --> 00:52:27,502
Alcatraz.

796
00:52:27,661 --> 00:52:30,989
It was built by the military
during the Civil War.

797
00:52:31,622 --> 00:52:35,550
In May of '33, the War Department
abandoned the island.

798
00:52:35,703 --> 00:52:39,992
It was leveled, all except for the lower floor,
which is now used for storage.

799
00:52:40,143 --> 00:52:43,112
I have to get access to the lower level...

800
00:52:43,264 --> 00:52:46,352
...because that's where the dungeons have
gotta be located.

801
00:52:46,505 --> 00:52:50,827
The only guard on record to be fired
or dismissed during Henri's solitary time...

802
00:52:50,985 --> 00:52:52,906
...was Derek Simpson.

803
00:52:53,066 --> 00:52:54,627
Locate Simpson.

804
00:52:54,786 --> 00:52:58,791
The prison opened in June of '34
under Warden Humson.

805
00:52:58,947 --> 00:53:01,675
He insisted on a high level
of guards to prisoners.

806
00:53:01,827 --> 00:53:03,836
Glenn was the first appointee.

807
00:53:05,268 --> 00:53:06,632
Mr. Henkin.

808
00:53:06,788 --> 00:53:08,589
First, you work for me.

809
00:53:08,749 --> 00:53:11,477
- I was just on my way.
- Let me finish.

810
00:53:11,869 --> 00:53:14,914
You work for me, which means
when I call you, you drop everything.

811
00:53:15,070 --> 00:53:17,952
You return my call or you will cease
to work for me.

812
00:53:18,110 --> 00:53:21,952
I don't care if you're holed up
with Rita Hayworth. Understand?

813
00:53:22,111 --> 00:53:24,195
- Yes, sir.
- Good.

814
00:53:25,712 --> 00:53:28,561
Now, what the hell
you think you're doing with this trial?

815
00:53:28,712 --> 00:53:29,957
Trying to defend my client.

816
00:53:30,113 --> 00:53:32,317
Then why don't you defend him
for chrissake?

817
00:53:32,474 --> 00:53:34,919
Knock down the charges,
say it was a crime of passion...

818
00:53:35,074 --> 00:53:37,923
...or figure out how
you're gonna cross-examine witnesses...

819
00:53:38,074 --> 00:53:42,156
...instead of this psychological coma crap
that doesn't mean anything in a court of law.

820
00:53:42,315 --> 00:53:44,956
But, sir, I think it does.
As long as this is my case-

821
00:53:45,116 --> 00:53:49,798
Fair enough. I tried to talk reasonably
to you, but you're not going for it...

822
00:53:49,956 --> 00:53:52,838
...so you're not handling this case anymore.
Done.

823
00:53:52,997 --> 00:53:54,722
Mr. Henkin...

824
00:53:55,118 --> 00:53:58,643
...they're printing my opening statement
in 250 newspapers across the country.

825
00:53:58,798 --> 00:54:02,160
If you wanna take me off this because
you're afraid of taking on Alcatraz...

826
00:54:02,319 --> 00:54:03,727
...that's your choice.

827
00:54:03,879 --> 00:54:07,240
But I'm just gonna go to Jerry Hoolihan
and tell my side of the story.

828
00:54:07,640 --> 00:54:11,601
If you wanna play hardball, sir,
I'll play hardball too.

829
00:54:16,802 --> 00:54:18,450
I'm trying to be your friend, James.

830
00:54:19,322 --> 00:54:21,166
Do you know who the warden
of Alcatraz is?

831
00:54:21,323 --> 00:54:23,724
He is the most respected warden
in this country...

832
00:54:23,883 --> 00:54:26,284
...dealing with
the world's hardest criminals.

833
00:54:26,443 --> 00:54:29,292
If you try to make Humson
look like a Nazi...

834
00:54:29,444 --> 00:54:32,009
...they will eat you for breakfast.

835
00:54:39,725 --> 00:54:43,251
Henri, you are gonna die if I can't
get corroboration about what goes on there.

836
00:54:43,407 --> 00:54:46,496
I need names. Names of men
who'll come and testify.

837
00:54:46,647 --> 00:54:49,692
What makes you think
these men are gonna come and testify?

838
00:54:49,848 --> 00:54:51,768
Maybe you got some friends
you don't know about.

839
00:54:53,328 --> 00:54:56,373
- You wanna play cards?
- I can get a court order. Make them testify.

840
00:54:56,529 --> 00:54:58,897
What's your court order do for them
back on the Rock'?

841
00:54:59,050 --> 00:55:01,331
Mr. Glenn gonna kill them, that's what.

842
00:55:01,490 --> 00:55:04,372
This is the only chance we've got.
We're talking about your life.

843
00:55:04,531 --> 00:55:08,253
For a smart guy, you're awful slow.
I'm already dead. I told you that.

844
00:55:08,411 --> 00:55:12,176
You know, you can't change Alcatraz
It just is.

845
00:55:12,332 --> 00:55:13,621
So why fight it?

846
00:55:13,772 --> 00:55:17,614
I see you standing up in court preaching.
I don't even know what you're talking about.

847
00:55:17,773 --> 00:55:20,054
Justice. I'm talking about justice.

848
00:55:20,213 --> 00:55:22,941
Jim, I killed him, they saw it,
they gonna kill me.

849
00:55:23,094 --> 00:55:24,938
Nothing you say
gonna make any difference.

850
00:55:25,095 --> 00:55:27,496
So I don't see
what you got to get so excited about.

851
00:55:27,655 --> 00:55:31,257
This trial doesn't interest you at all?
You don't care about it in the slightest?

852
00:55:31,416 --> 00:55:35,738
Well, you know, you look like
you're having a good time, so I mean...

853
00:55:35,896 --> 00:55:37,784
No, I don't care.

854
00:55:37,937 --> 00:55:42,302
Main thing is, I got a friend my age
to talk to till they gas me.

855
00:55:42,458 --> 00:55:46,943
I'm not your friend, Henri, I'm your attorney.
I'm trying to save your life. Guard.

856
00:55:47,098 --> 00:55:50,187
You know, I had a sister...

857
00:55:50,339 --> 00:55:52,740
...but I ain't seen her
since they put me in jail.

858
00:55:52,900 --> 00:55:55,061
I got nothing. I got nobody.

859
00:55:55,220 --> 00:55:58,309
I don't need a lawyer. I need a friend.

860
00:55:58,460 --> 00:56:01,865
And this so you can prove something
to some guy named Darrow or something...

861
00:56:02,021 --> 00:56:06,027
...you're not doing that for me.
Hey, hey, you wanna do something for me'?

862
00:56:06,182 --> 00:56:08,343
Let's play cards.

863
00:56:10,503 --> 00:56:12,708
You go ahead and play cards.
I got a case to try.

864
00:56:12,863 --> 00:56:15,744
Jim. Jim, Jim? Where are you going?

865
00:56:15,904 --> 00:56:18,228
Where are you going? Hey.

866
00:56:26,666 --> 00:56:27,954
I'm Henri Young's attorney.

867
00:56:28,106 --> 00:56:29,667
I'd like to ask you a few questions.

868
00:56:29,827 --> 00:56:33,188
I'm gonna call prisoners to the stand
to testify about life on Alcatraz.

869
00:56:33,347 --> 00:56:34,952
I wanna know where the dungeons are.

870
00:56:35,107 --> 00:56:37,268
What solitary time
in those dungeons is like.

871
00:56:37,428 --> 00:56:39,436
I want the jury to know and understand.

872
00:56:39,589 --> 00:56:42,317
You tell them to get caught
robbing a bank. They'll find out.

873
00:56:43,269 --> 00:56:45,190
I'm done talking.

874
00:56:58,952 --> 00:57:01,517
Mr. Murphy, if we can get
decent treatment for you...

875
00:57:01,673 --> 00:57:04,358
...it makes decent treatment possible
for everyone.

876
00:57:04,513 --> 00:57:08,879
If we ignore cruelty in one place,
it makes it more acceptable everywhere.

877
00:57:09,034 --> 00:57:11,282
I ain't gonna do shit for you.

878
00:57:11,434 --> 00:57:14,119
You can't get me no good time
knocked off.

879
00:57:14,275 --> 00:57:15,956
You can't get me no privileges.

880
00:57:16,115 --> 00:57:18,636
You can't even get me
seconds at dessert.

881
00:57:18,796 --> 00:57:23,118
If I testify for anybody, I testify for the DA.
He's got some juice here.

882
00:57:27,557 --> 00:57:29,522
Mr. Baker, could you tell me anything...

883
00:57:29,677 --> 00:57:30,757
...about Henri Young?

884
00:57:30,918 --> 00:57:33,122
Don't know Henri Young.

885
00:57:33,759 --> 00:57:37,164
Could you tell us anything
about Mr. Glenn?

886
00:57:38,359 --> 00:57:41,361
Warden Glenn has always been
good to me.

887
00:57:43,160 --> 00:57:45,561
Have you ever been in the dungeons?

888
00:57:45,841 --> 00:57:48,002
Ma'am, I don't know nothing
about no dungeons.

889
00:57:48,881 --> 00:57:52,363
That's all, ma'am. I gotta go now.

890
00:57:56,003 --> 00:57:57,531
Fuck you.

891
00:57:57,683 --> 00:57:58,850
Did Mr. Glenn tell you...

892
00:57:59,004 --> 00:58:00,564
...not to cooperate with me?

893
00:58:00,723 --> 00:58:02,207
Fuck you.

894
00:58:02,364 --> 00:58:04,765
Where are the dungeons located?

895
00:58:04,924 --> 00:58:07,805
Don't take my fucking picture.

896
00:58:11,285 --> 00:58:13,566
Did you know I can get a writ
of habeas corpus...

897
00:58:13,726 --> 00:58:16,411
...that can force you to come
and testify in a court of law?

898
00:58:16,567 --> 00:58:18,576
Fuck you.

899
00:58:19,327 --> 00:58:21,291
Thank you very much for your time.

900
00:58:21,447 --> 00:58:23,292
Don't mention it.

901
00:58:23,447 --> 00:58:26,689
And you, sweetheart?

902
00:58:26,849 --> 00:58:29,534
I'd like to fuck you.

903
00:58:44,692 --> 00:58:47,574
Well, I hope your day has been fruitful.

904
00:58:48,533 --> 00:58:52,015
I don't see your photographer.
Is he still taking pictures?

905
00:58:52,173 --> 00:58:54,018
He's trying to.

906
00:58:54,173 --> 00:58:56,574
We're not receiving a great deal
of cooperation.

907
00:58:56,734 --> 00:59:00,259
It almost seems someone spoke to the
prisoners and told them not to talk to us.

908
00:59:00,415 --> 00:59:03,459
There's no conspiracy.
No one talked to them.

909
00:59:03,616 --> 00:59:06,497
Maybe it's because they are
dangerous people who belong here.

910
00:59:06,656 --> 00:59:08,664
They have no interest
in you or your case.

911
00:59:08,817 --> 00:59:12,058
I would like to see the dungeons.
- I'm sorry? Dungeons?

912
00:59:12,377 --> 00:59:14,538
The old Citadel, the sub-level of the prison.

913
00:59:14,698 --> 00:59:19,140
That's mostly storage,
a few solitary cells. No dungeons.

914
00:59:19,298 --> 00:59:22,463
I would like to see
the solitary-confinement cells.

915
00:59:22,619 --> 00:59:25,107
I would love to show those cells to you,
but I can't.

916
00:59:25,260 --> 00:59:29,461
They're an insurance risk to visitors in case
of a riot. We won't be able to protect you.

917
00:59:29,620 --> 00:59:31,465
Thank you for your concern.

918
00:59:31,620 --> 00:59:33,781
I could show you
the exercise yard, though.

919
00:59:34,661 --> 00:59:36,822
You have papers.

920
00:59:36,981 --> 00:59:39,906
Yes, I have papers.
So you can cut the good-guy act.

921
00:59:40,062 --> 00:59:44,068
Mr. Stamphill, the fact is I do consider
myself as one of the good guys...

922
00:59:44,223 --> 00:59:48,272
...and perhaps more than you,
I know what the bad guys are like.

923
00:59:48,424 --> 00:59:50,825
No, no, no. I'd like to read them. Please.

924
00:59:52,104 --> 00:59:53,545
Thank you.

925
00:59:55,145 --> 00:59:56,269
That is a court order...

926
00:59:56,426 --> 00:59:59,754
...instructing you to permit us access
to the solitary-confinement cells.

927
00:59:59,906 --> 01:00:02,994
And allow the photographer, Mr. Kelly,
to take pictures of the same...

928
01:00:03,147 --> 01:00:05,832
...to be used as exhibits in the trial
of People v. Young.

929
01:00:05,987 --> 01:00:07,952
You are also instructed
to hand over to us...

930
01:00:08,107 --> 01:00:11,752
...the complete medical
and disciplinary files as to therein.

931
01:00:11,908 --> 01:00:13,513
If you refuse to do so...

932
01:00:13,669 --> 01:00:16,309
you will have to appear in court
and show just cause.

933
01:00:23,070 --> 01:00:25,438
Why don't you take
Miss McCasslin out for some air?

934
01:00:25,591 --> 01:00:28,952
- I was instructed not to leave you alone.
- I don't care.

935
01:00:29,111 --> 01:00:32,113
You may be used to these conditions
but obviously she's not.

936
01:00:32,272 --> 01:00:33,560
We've already been searched.

937
01:00:33,713 --> 01:00:36,594
Why don't you take her outside?
Or else we can go right to Glenn.

938
01:00:36,753 --> 01:00:40,158
All right. All right. No more photos.

939
01:00:40,594 --> 01:00:42,002
You all right?

940
01:00:42,154 --> 01:00:43,321
Thanks, Mike.

941
01:00:43,474 --> 01:00:44,642
I just need some air.

942
01:01:07,238 --> 01:01:09,126
My God.

943
01:01:28,283 --> 01:01:31,972
Listen, my name's James Stamphill.
I'm Henri Young's attorney.

944
01:01:32,123 --> 01:01:34,568
I can force them to let you out
so you can testify...

945
01:01:34,724 --> 01:01:36,492
...in San Francisco in a court of law.

946
01:01:36,644 --> 01:01:40,606
You just have to give me your name.
I promise I will do what I said for you.

947
01:01:54,407 --> 01:01:55,487
Hey, James, she's okay.

948
01:01:55,647 --> 01:01:57,415
Just needed some air.

949
01:02:00,649 --> 01:02:03,650
Can we go now?
- Feeling any better?

950
01:02:04,449 --> 01:02:06,533
I guess I'll make it.

951
01:02:09,690 --> 01:02:13,051
- Did you get anything?
- I got three names.

952
01:02:13,731 --> 01:02:15,292
Let's go.

953
01:02:16,251 --> 01:02:18,816
Where did Stamphill get
the three names on this list?

954
01:02:22,373 --> 01:02:23,540
I don't know, Mr. Henkin.

955
01:02:23,693 --> 01:02:25,657
You think you can trust these cons?

956
01:02:25,814 --> 01:02:28,138
They're smart enough
to look after their interests.

957
01:02:28,293 --> 01:02:31,382
They told Glenn your boy James said
he'd get them out of solitary...

958
01:02:31,535 --> 01:02:34,263
...as long as they testify for the defense
and lie on the stand.

959
01:02:34,415 --> 01:02:35,419
That's a lie.

960
01:02:35,575 --> 01:02:37,255
He wanted to find one convict willing-

961
01:02:37,416 --> 01:02:39,544
Mary, Mary, this is goddamn bribery.

962
